  "opinion": "As a retired Italian man who spent his early years in the shadow of a single parent’s modest education, I’ve observed how stereotypes can quietly erode potential. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just about fear—it’s the invisible weight of expectations that make someone doubt their own abilities. When a young woman sees herself as ‘not a math person,’ or a boy feels pressured to be ‘the smart one,’ it’s not just a momentary doubt; it’s a pattern that shapes entire careers. In my time, as a creative problem-solver who once built bridges from scratch in Rome’s old city, I’ve seen how a single misstep in a project can lead to a lifetime of self-doubt. Addressing this isn’t about grand gestures—it’s about small, consistent actions. For instance, in my board game nights with neighbors, I’ve encouraged kids to explore ideas without fear of judgment. If we can create spaces where curiosity trumps conformity, where the fear of being labeled doesn’t stop someone from trying, then STEM can become a place where everyone feels they belong. The key is to recognize that stereotypes aren’t just about numbers or test scores; they’re about the human spirit. We must nurture the next generation with the same patience and creativity that I learned from my own community.",
